# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: air-gun
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The **10 metre air pistol** is an Olympic shooting event governed by the International Shooting Sport Federation (ISSF).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] It is similar to 10 metre air rifle in that it is shot with 4.5 mm (or .177) caliber air guns at a distance of 10 metres (11 yards), and that the match consists of a qualification round of 60 competition shots within 75 minutes.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] If an electronic scoring system (EST) is not available, 15 minutes are added to the time limit.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Competitors are allowed to shoot an unlimited number of shots during the 15 minutes preparation and sighting time.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Along with the 50 meter pistol, it is considered a precision shooting event.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Thus, numerous shooters compete in both events.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] There are some restrictions on the pistol regarding its dimensions, weight and trigger pull weight.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] It must be operated by one hand only from a standing, unsupported position.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The shooter decides their own tempo as long as the maximum time is not exceeded.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] After the qualification round, the shooters with the top eight scores move on to a final round consisting of 24 competition shots.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] After the tenth shot, individual commands are given so that the audience may follow the progress of the standings.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The major competitions are the Olympic Games every four years and the ISSF World Shooting Championships every four years.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] In addition, the event is included in ISSF World Cups and in continental championships, as well as in many other international and national competitions.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] It is an indoor sport and, at the highest level, electronic targets are used instead of the traditional paper targets.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The air pistol range is the same as the air rifle range, giving each shooter a table, a 1 meter wide firing point, and a 10-meter distance between the firing line and the target line.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The current rules require ranges to be built indoors, with specified minimum requirements for artificial lighting.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The distance from floor level to the centre of the target is 1400mm ± 50mm.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Many larger and top-level competitions are held on temporary ranges installed in multi-use sporting facilities or convention centers.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The target, 17 by 17 cm (6.7 by 6.7 in), is traditionally made of light-coloured cardboard upon which scoring lines and a black aiming mark consisting of the score zones 7 through 10 are printed.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] There is also an inner ten ring, but the number of inner tens is used only for tie-breaking.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The changing of these traditional targets is handled by each shooter by means of electronic—or more archaically, manually operated—carrier devices.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] In major competitions, only one shot may be fired on each target, a number that can increase to two, five, or even ten with lowering level and importance of the competition.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Used targets are collected by range officials to be scored in a separate office.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] During the last few decades, these paper targets have been gradually replaced by electronic target systems, which immediately display the results on monitors.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] When using these systems, actual scoring lines are not printed, but the location of the impact hole (which can be determined acoustically) is automatically converted into corresponding scores by a computer.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] ISSF rules now require the use of these systems in top-level competitions.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] They are generally used in other international competitions as well, and in some countries they are even common in national competitions.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] To promote comfortable and accurate shooting from a standing position, match air pistols must have fast lock times, shoot with little recoil or vibration, and exhibit minimal movement and balance shifts during discharge.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The pistol must also be able to be tailored by adjustable user interfaces and various accessories to an individual shooter's personal preferences.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Combined with appropriate match pellets, the pistol must produce a consistent 10-ring performance so that a non maximal result during the initial phase can be attributed to the participant.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The pistols used are gas-driven with a caliber of 4.5 mm (0.18 in).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The minimum trigger pull weight is 500 grams (18 ounces), half that of a sport pistol.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The grip restrictions are similar to sport pistols, but the box in which an air pistol must fit is larger: 42 by 20 by 5 cm (16.5 by 7.9 by 2.0 in).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] This allows for longer sight lines and also gives room for cocking arms, although with a few exceptions (such as the Baikal IZH-46M) modern match air pistols use pre-filled air, or less commonly carbon dioxide, containers.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The maximum overall weight is 1.5 kg (3.31 lb).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The pistol must be operated by only one hand from a standing position, and may be loaded with only one pellet at a time.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] For the 10 metre air pistol and air rifle disciplines match, diabolo pellets are used.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] These pellets have wadcutter heads, meaning the front is (nearly) flat, which leave clean round holes in paper targets for easy scoring.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Match pellets are offered in tins and more elaborate packages that avoid deformation and other damage that could impair their uniformity.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Air gunners are encouraged to perform shooting group tests with their gun clamped in a machine rest to establish which particular match pellet type performs best for their particular air gun.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] To facilitate maximum performance out of various air guns, the leading match pellet manufacturers produce pellets with graduated "head sizes", which means the pellets are offered with front diameters from 4.48 mm up to 4.51 mm.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] As in other ISSF pistol events, clothing that restricts the movement of joints for support is not allowed.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Optical aids such as iris diaphragms or prescription glasses are allowed as long as they are not mounted on the pistol, which may have open sights only.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Though shooting glasses are extremely customizable, most pairs contain three basic elements: a lens, a mechanical iris, and a blinder.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] These components work together to help shooters focus on both the faraway target and their gun's sights at the same time.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Ear protection is recommended by the ISSF as well as by coaches, who sometimes stress their usefulness in shutting out distracting noise rather than their necessity for safety reasons (paramount in other shooting disciplines).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] It is each shooter's responsibility to get his or her pistol and shoes validated in a specific area (the equipment control) prior to starting the competition.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] To discourage shooters from lowering the trigger pull weight after passing equipment control, random controls are conducted after the match.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Failure to pass such controls results in immediate disqualification.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Shooters are generally divided into four classes: men, junior men, women and junior women.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The junior classes are included in most championships, with some notable exceptions (such as the Olympic Games and the ISSF World Cups).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] A shooter remains a junior up to and including the calendar year in which he or she becomes 21 years of age, although a junior may opt to participate in the main class instead.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] In both the qualification stage and the final stage, all shooting is supervised by a Chief Range Officer, whose duties include responsibility for the correct behaviour of all personnel, dealing with technical irregularities, and cooperation with the jury.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] For the qualification stage, the shooters are divided as necessary into relays.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Each relay starts with a 15-minute preparation time during which the shooter may fire an unlimited number of sighting shots.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Afterwards, the Chief Range Officer gives the command "match firing, start", indicating the start of the competition time.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] 60 competition shots must be shot within a 75-minute period time (90 minutes if no electronic targets are available).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The 60 shots are usually organized in 6 ten-shot series for display on scoreboards.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The top eight shooters in the qualification round advance to the final.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Often, many shooters have the same score.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The higher number of inner tens is the first tiebreaker.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] If two or more shooters have the same number of inner tens, the shooter with the highest score in the last ten-shot series is placed higher.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] During the final, the score zones are divided into tenths (by means of a special gauge, in the absence of automatic scoring devices), so that each hit can give up to 10.9 points instead of the maximum 10 during the qualification.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Electronic targets are required by the ISSF for finals at the Olympic Games, ISSF World Cups and ISSF World Championships.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] After a five-minute sighting shot period and the presentation of the athletes to the audience, the athletes have 250 seconds to shoot five shots after the command "for the first competition series, load, start".
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The same command is given again for a second five shot series.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] After the tenth shot, separate commands are given for each competition shot with a time limit of 50 seconds per shot.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] After each two shots, the athlete with the lowest score is eliminated until two shooters are left to compete for the first place in the 23rd and 24th shot.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Current rules were introduced in 2017 after the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The air pistol event was introduced on the World Championship level in 1970, and on the Olympic programme in 1988.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Before 1985, when finals began to be used, championships were decided by the results of the 40 or 60 shot match (40 for women and 60 for men).
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Before 1982, the men's match also consisted of 40 shots.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] As in many other ISSF events, the target for air pistol was reduced in size in 1989, also lowering the scores (although not by much), and thereby resetting all records.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The development after this shows a contrast to that of air rifle shooting: whereas in air rifle the winning score of the 1989 World Championships would not have reached the final 17 years later, the same result increase has not occurred in air pistol.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Sergei Pyzhianov's world record of 593 points, set in the first World Cup Final with the new targets, remained unbeaten for almost 20 years until Jin Jong-oh set a new one with 594 points in at the ISSF World Cup Changwon 2009.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Although competitions are no longer held outdoors, the most important competitions (Olympics, World Championships, World Cups) are still scheduled for the Northern Hemisphere summer season because they are combined with outdoor events such as 50m rifle and 25m pistol events.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Many lesser international events, however, are held during the European indoor season between October and March, culminating in the European Championships each year.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] Most of these competitions are multi-day events held together with air rifle matches.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] The ISSF publishes lists of historical champions.
[src:air-gun/10-m-air-pistol] A green background indicates the Olympic champion.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] The **.177 caliber** or **4.5 mm caliber** is the smallest diameter of pellets and BB shots widely used in air guns, and is the only caliber generally accepted for formal target competition.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] It is also sometimes used for hunting small game, like fowl.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] It is also used in field target competitions, where it competes with .20 caliber (5 mm) and .22 caliber (5.6 mm) rifles.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] Steel BBs are typically slightly smaller than lead BBs at 0.175-inch (4.4 mm) diameter, although the bore diameter of the barrel are the same.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] Some air guns are designed to accept .177 pellets, .177 lead shot, or .175 steel BBs interchangeably.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] If two guns fire pellets of different weights, the gun firing the lighter pellet must fire it at a higher velocity to achieve the same muzzle energy.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] This is an important consideration in locations where air guns are legally restricted by muzzle energy.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] Because a .177 pellet is lighter than a larger caliber pellet of similar design, the .177 pellet can be propelled faster and therefore on a flatter trajectory, without exceeding the legal limit on energy.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] However, because the lighter projectile has a lower ballistic coefficient, it loses its initial energy to air resistance faster than a heavier, slower pellet.
[src:air-gun/177-caliber] Therefore, a heavier pellet (typically of a larger caliber) may be preferred for hunting.
[src:air-gun/22-caliber] Cartridges in this caliber include the very widely used .22 Long Rifle and .223 Remington/5.56×45mm NATO.
[src:air-gun/22-caliber] .22 inch is also a popular air gun pellet caliber, second only to the ubiquitous .177 caliber.
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] The **7.62 mm caliber** is a nominal caliber used for a number of different cartridges.
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] Historically, this class of cartridge was commonly known as **.30 caliber**, the equivalent in Imperial and United States Customary measures.
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] It is most commonly used in hunting cartridges.
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] The measurement equals 0.30 inches or three decimal lines, written ***.3″*** and read as ***three-line***.
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] The 7.62 mm designation refers to the internal diameter of the barrel at the lands (the raised helical ridges in rifled gun barrels).
[src:air-gun/30-caliber] The actual bullet caliber is often 7.82 mm (0.308 in), although Soviet weapons commonly use a 7.91 mm (0.311 in) bullet, as do older British (.303 British) and Japanese (7.7×58mm Arisaka) cartridges.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The **.38 Special**, also commonly known as **.38 S&W Special** (not to be confused with .38 S&W), **.38 Smith & Wesson Special**, **.38 Spl**, **.38 Spc** (pronounced "thirty-eight special"), or **9×29mmR** is a rimmed, centerfire cartridge designed by Smith & Wesson.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The .38 Special was the standard service cartridge for most United States police departments from the 1920s to the 1990s.
[src:air-gun/38-special] It was also a common sidearm cartridge used by United States military personnel in World War I, World War II, the Korean War, and the Vietnam War.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In other parts of the world, it is known by its metric designation of **9×29.5mmR** or **9.1×29mmR**.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Known for its accuracy and manageable recoil, the .38 Special remains one of the most popular revolver cartridges in the world more than a century after its introduction.
[src:air-gun/38-special] It is used for recreational target shooting, formal target competition, personal defense, and small-game hunting.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The .38 Special was designed and entered production in 1898 as an improvement over the .38 Long Colt which, as a military service cartridge, was found to have inadequate stopping power against the charges of Filipino Muslim warriors during the Philippine–American War.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Upon its introduction, the .38 Special was originally loaded with black powder, but the cartridge's popularity caused manufacturers to offer smokeless powder loadings within a year of its introduction.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Despite its name, the caliber of the .38 Special cartridge is actually .357 inches (36 caliber/9.07 mm), with the ".38" referring to the approximate diameter of the loaded brass case.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Except for case length, the .38 Special is identical to the .38 Short Colt, .38 Long Colt, and .357 Magnum.
[src:air-gun/38-special] This nearly identical nature of the three rounds allows a .38 Special round to be safely fired in revolvers chambered for .357 Magnum.
[src:air-gun/38-special] It also allows .38 Short Colt and .38 Long Colt rounds to be safely fired in revolvers chambered for .38 Special.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Thus, the .38 Special round and revolvers chambered for it have a unique versatility.
[src:air-gun/38-special] However, the longer and more powerful .357 Magnum cartridge will usually not chamber and fire in weapons rated specifically for .38 Special (e.g., all versions of the Smith & Wesson Model 10), which are not designed to handle the greatly increased pressure of magnum rounds.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Both .38 Special and .357 Magnum will chamber in Colt New Army revolvers in .38 Long Colt due to their straight-walled chambers, but this should not be done under any circumstances, due to dangerous pressure levels up to three times what the New Army is designed to withstand.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The .38 Special was designed and produced in 1898 as a higher-velocity round with better penetration than the .38 Long Colt, which was in government service in the Philippines during the Spanish–American War.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The .38 Long Colt revolver round would not penetrate the shields of the insurgent Philippine Moro warriors, and the government contracted with Smith & Wesson for a new revolver round.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The .38 Special held a minimum of 21 grains of black powder, 3 grains more than the then-current .38 Long Colt, and muzzle velocity (with a 158 grain bullet) was 100–150 feet per second greater.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In the late 1920s, in response to demands for a more effective law-enforcement cartridge, a new standard-velocity load for the .38 Special was developed by Western Cartridge Company.
[src:air-gun/38-special] This .38 Special variant, which incorporated a 200 grains (13 g) round-nosed lead 'Lubaloy' bullet, was named the .38 Super Police.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Remington-Peters also introduced a similar loading.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Testing revealed that the longer, heavier 200-grain (13 g) .357-calibre bullet, fired at low velocity, tended to 'keyhole' or tumble upon impact, providing greater shock effect against unprotected personnel.
[src:air-gun/38-special] At the same time, authorities in Great Britain, who had decided to adopt the .38 caliber revolver as a replacement for their existing .455 service cartridge, also tested the same 200-grain (13.0 g) bullet in the smaller .38 S&W cartridge.
[src:air-gun/38-special] This cartridge was called the .38 S&W Super Police or the 38/200.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Britain later adopted the 38/200 as its standard military handgun cartridge.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In 1930, Smith & Wesson introduced a large-frame .38 Special revolver with a 5-inch barrel and fixed sights, intended for police use: the Smith & Wesson 38/44 Heavy Duty.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The following year, a new high-power loading called the .38 Special Hi-Speed with a 158-grain (10.2 g) metal-tip bullet was developed for these revolvers in response to requests from law enforcement agencies for a handgun bullet that could penetrate auto bodies and body armor.
[src:air-gun/38-special] That same year, Colt Firearms announced that their Colt Official Police would also handle 'high-speed' .38 Special loadings.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The 38/44 high-speed cartridge came in three bullet weights: 158 grains (10.2 g), 150 grains (9.7 g), and 110 grains (7.1 g), with either coated lead or steel jacket, metal-piercing bullets.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The media attention gathered by the 38/44 and its ammunition eventually led Smith & Wesson to develop a completely new cartridge with a longer case length in 1934.
[src:air-gun/38-special] During World War II, some U.S. aircrew (primarily Navy and Marine Corps) were issued .38 Special S&W Victory revolvers as sidearms for use in the event of a forced landing.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In May 1943, a new .38 Special cartridge with a 158-grain (10.2 g), full-steel-jacketed, copper flash-coated bullet meeting the requirements of the Hague Convention was developed at Springfield Armory and adopted for the Smith & Wesson revolvers.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The new military .38 Special loading propelled its 158 grains (10.2 g) bullet at a standard 850 ft/s (260 m/s) from a 4-inch (100 mm) revolver barrel.
[src:air-gun/38-special] During the war, many U.S. naval and Marine aircrew were also issued red-tipped 38 Special tracer ammunition using either a 120 or 158 gr (7.8 or 10.2 g) bullet for emergency signaling purposes.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Air Force adopted the *Cartridge, Caliber 38, Ball M41*, a military variant of the .38 Special cartridge designed to conform to Hague Convention rules.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The original 38 M41 ball cartridge used a 130-grain full-metal-jacketed bullet, and was loaded to an average pressure of only 13,000 pounds per square inch (90 MPa), giving a muzzle velocity of approximately 725 ft/s (221 m/s) from a 4-inch (100 mm) barrel.
[src:air-gun/38-special] This ammunition was intended to prolong the life of S&W M12 and Colt Aircrewman revolvers equipped with aluminum cylinders and frames, which were prone to stress fractures when fired with standard 38 Special ammunition.
[src:air-gun/38-special] By 1961, a slightly revised M41 38-caliber cartridge specification, known as the *Cartridge, Caliber 38 Ball, Special, M41*, had been adopted for U.S. armed forces using 38 Special-caliber handguns.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The M41 ball cartridge was first used in .38 Special revolvers carried by USAF aircrew and Strategic Air Command security police, and by 1961 was in use by the U.S.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Army for security police, dog handlers, and other personnel equipped with 38 Special caliber revolvers.
[src:air-gun/38-special] A variant of the standard M41 cartridge with a semi-pointed, unjacketed lead bullet was later adopted for CONUS (Continental United States) police and security personnel.
[src:air-gun/38-special] At the same time, .38 Special tracer cartridges were reintroduced by the US Navy, Marines, and Air Force to provide a means of emergency signaling by downed aircrew.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Tracer cartridges in .38 Special caliber, in different colors, were issued, generally as part of a standard aircrew survival vest kit.
[src:air-gun/38-special] A request for more powerful .38 Special ammunition for use by Air Police and security personnel resulted in the *Caliber 38 Special, Ball, PGU-12/B High Velocity* cartridge.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Air Force, the PGU-12/B had a greatly increased maximum allowable pressure rating of 20,000 psi, sufficient to propel a 130-grain FMJ bullet at 1,125 ft/s (343 m/s) from a solid 6-inch (150 mm) test barrel, and about 950–1,000 ft/s from a 4-inch (100 mm) revolver barrel.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The PGU-12/B *High Velocity* cartridge differs from M41 *Special* ammunition in two important respects—the *PGU-12/B* is a much higher-pressure cartridge, with a bullet deeply set and crimped into the cartridge case.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In 1972, the Federal Bureau of Investigation introduced a new .38 Special +P loading that became known as the "FBI Load".
[src:air-gun/38-special] The FBI Load combined a more powerful powder charge with a 158-grain unjacketed soft lead semi-wadcutter hollow-point bullet designed to readily expand at typical .38 Special velocities obtained in revolvers commonly used by law enforcement.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The FBI Load proved very satisfactory in effectively stopping adversaries in numerous documented shootings using 2- to 4-inch barreled revolvers.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The FBI Load was later adopted by the Chicago Police Department and numerous other law enforcement agencies.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Demand for a .38 Special cartridge with even greater performance for law enforcement led to the introduction of the +P+ .38 Special cartridge, first introduced by Federal and Winchester.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Due to its black-powder heritage, the .38 Special is a low-pressure cartridge, one of the lowest in common use today at 17,000 psi.
[src:air-gun/38-special] By modern standards, the .38 Special fires a medium-sized bullet at rather low speeds.
[src:air-gun/38-special] In the case of target loads, a 148 gr (9.6 g) bullet is propelled to only 690 ft/s (210 m/s).
[src:air-gun/38-special] The closest comparisons are the 380 ACP, which fires much lighter bullets slightly faster than most .38 Special loads; the 9×19mm Parabellum, which fires a somewhat lighter bullet significantly faster; and the .38 Super, which fires a comparable bullet considerably faster.
[src:air-gun/38-special] All of these cartridges are usually found in semi-automatic pistols.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The higher-pressure .38 Special +P loads at 20,000 psi offer about 20% more muzzle energy than standard-pressure loads, which places them between the .380 ACP and the 9mm Parabellum; similar to that of the 9×18mm Makarov.
[src:air-gun/38-special] A few specialty manufacturers' +P loads for this cartridge can attain even higher energies than that, especially when fired from longer barrels, producing energies in the range of the 9mm Parabellum.
[src:air-gun/38-special] These loads are generally not recommended for older revolvers or ones not specifically "+P" rated.
[src:air-gun/38-special] All of the above specifications for 38 loadings, and the .357 Magnum, are applicable when fired from a 6-inch (150 mm) barreled revolver.
[src:air-gun/38-special] The velocity is reduced when using 4-inch (100 mm) barreled guns.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Power (muzzle energy) will, of course, decrease accordingly.
[src:air-gun/38-special] Although only a few US police departments now issue or authorize use of the .38 Special revolver as a standard-duty weapon, the caliber remains popular with some police officers for use in short-barreled revolvers carried when off duty or for undercover police investigations.
[src:air-gun/38-special] It is also widely used in revolvers purchased for civilian home defense or for concealed carry.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The **.45 ACP** (Automatic Colt Pistol), also known as **.45 Auto**, **.45 Automatic**, or **11.43×23mm** is a rimless straight-walled handgun cartridge designed by John Moses Browning in 1904, for use in his prototype Colt semi-automatic pistol.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] After successful military trials, it was adopted as the standard chambering for Colt's M1911 pistol.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The round was developed due to a lack of stopping power experienced in the Moro Rebellion in places like Sulu.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The issued ammunition, .38 Long Colt, had proved inadequate, motivating the search for a better cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This experience and the Thompson–LaGarde Tests of 1904 led the Army and the Cavalry to decide that a minimum of .45 caliber was required in a new handgun cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The standard-issue military .45 ACP cartridge uses a 230 gr (15 g; 0.53 oz) round-nose bullet at approximately 830 ft/s (250 m/s) fired from a government-issue M1911A1 pistol.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It operates at a relatively low maximum chamber pressure rating of 21,000 psi (140 MPa), compared to 35,000 psi (240 MPa) for both 9mm Parabellum and .40 S&W, which due to a low bolt thrust helps extend the service lives of weapons.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Since standard-pressure .45 ACP rounds are subsonic when fired from handguns and submachine guns, it is a useful caliber for suppressed weapons as it lacks the sonic boom inherent to supersonic rounds.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] During the late 19th century and early 20th centuries, the United States Cavalry began trials to replace their sidearm arsenal of issued Single Action Army (SAA) in favor of the more modern and versatile double-action revolver in .45 Colt.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] After the example of the Cavalry, the Army in turn had fielded versions of double-action revolvers in .38 Long Colt.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was eventually decided that the .38-caliber round was significantly less effective in overall "stopping power" than the .45 Automatic against determined opponents, such as the Tausug Moro juramentado warriors, who were encountered in the Moro Rebellion.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The standard-issue rifle, the .30-40 Krag, had also failed to stop Moro warriors effectively; the British had similar lack-of-stopping-power issues switching to the .303 British, which resulted in the development of the *dum-dum* bullet, in an attempt to compensate for the round's deficiencies.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This experience, and the Thompson–LaGarde Tests of 1904, led the Army and the Cavalry to decide a minimum of .45-caliber was required in a new handgun.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Thompson and Major Louis La Garde of the medical corps arranged tests on cadavers and animals in the Chicago stockyards, resulting in their declaring that the .45 was the most effective pistol cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] They noted, however, training was critical to make sure a soldier could score a hit in a vulnerable part of the body.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Colt had been working with Browning on a .41 caliber cartridge in 1904, and in 1905, when the Cavalry asked for a .45-caliber equivalent, Colt modified the pistol design to fire an enlarged version of the prototype .41 round.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The result from Colt was the Model 1905 and the new .45 ACP cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The resulting .45 caliber cartridge, named the ".45 ACP", was similar in performance to the .45 Schofield cartridge and only slightly less powerful while significantly shorter than the .45 Colt cartridge that the United States Cavalry was using at the time.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] By 1906, bids from six makers were submitted, among them, Browning's design, submitted by Colt.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Only DWM, Savage, and Colt made the first cut.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] DWM, which submitted two Luger pistols chambered in .45 ACP, withdrew from testing after the first round of tests, for unspecified reasons.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] During the second round of evaluations in 1910, the Colt design passed extensive testing with no failures, while the Savage design suffered 37 stoppages or parts failures.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The Colt pistol was adopted as the Model 1911.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The cartridge-pistol combination was quite successful but not satisfactory for U.S. military purposes.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Over time, a series of improved designs were offered, culminating in the adoption in 1911 of the "Cal.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] 45 Automatic Pistol Ball Cartridge, Model of 1911", a 1.273-inch-long (32 mm) round with a bullet weight of 230 grains (15 g).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The first production, at Frankford Arsenal, was marked "F A 8 11", for the August 1911 date.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The cartridge was designed by John Browning for Colt, but the most influential person in selecting the cartridge was Army ordnance member General John T.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] After the poor performance of the Army's .38 Long Colt pistols evidenced during the Philippine–American War (1899–1902), Thompson insisted on a more capable pistol cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The "T" (trials) designation was used for the experimental version of a cartridge and "M" (model) is used for the accepted and standardized version.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It came in either 24-round revolver ammo cartons, containing eight 3-round "half-moon" clips (1917-1945), pre-war 20-round cartons (1911-1942), or wartime 50-round cartons (1942–present).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The M12 and M15 shotshell rounds were packed in 20-round cartons sealed in heat-sealed foil-lined Kraft paper.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] was the standard full-metal jacketed lead-core bullet.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] has a hole drilled through the case and does not have a primer.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] has a tapered case and does not have a bullet.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] to allow pilots and aircrew armed with the Colt M1911A1 to use it for hunting small game.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The shotshell was a little longer than a standard round, so the operator had to load it in the action individually.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was extracted after firing by removing the magazine, pulling back the slide, and pushing down on the case until it fell down the magazine well.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Reports showed that the paper projectile was affected by humidity and would swell or break apart.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was made limited standard until replaced by the .45 M15 shot cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] was an improved survival round loaded with 108 pieces of No.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was loaded and extracted exactly like the M12 shot cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The round was designed as a short-ranged red flare for use in emergency signalling.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The "z" in the designation stands for cartridges loaded with nitrocellulose rather than cordite.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] (1917) was the British designation used for American-manufactured ammunition.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The Royal Navy had purchased a shipment of M1911 pistols in 1917 along with enough ammunition for evaluation, training and service purposes.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was never standardized by the Lists of Changes, but was mentioned in the Vocabulary of Priced Stores.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It came in seven-round packets and was manufactured by Winchester.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] (1940–1945) was the designation used for American-manufactured ammunition and proposed British manufacture of .45 M1911 ball.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Lend-lease ammunition came in commercial 42-round yellow Winchester or 50-round white Western Cartridge Company cartons.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] U.S. military-issue ammunition came in 20-round cartons, shifting to larger 50-round cartons in early 1942.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It was never manufactured in Britain because it was readily available from American forces.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] (1943) was a variant proposed for the Royal Navy, but never put into production.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] (1942–1946) was the Canadian designation for their domestically manufactured ammunition for use in the European theater.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It came in a plain 42-round carton that mimicked the capacity and dimensions of the yellow commercial Winchester ammunition cartons sold to Britain through Lend-lease.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] (1943–1956) was the Australian designation used for their domestically-manufactured ammunition for use in the Pacific theater.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Post-war production for use in the pistols and submachine guns given out by the US as military aid.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The .45 ACP has 25–27.4 grains (1.62–1.78 g) of H2O cartridge case capacity, depending on manufacturer and production lot.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] 45 Auto maximum CIP cartridge dimensions.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 1 in 16 in (406 mm), 6 grooves, Ø lands = .442 in (11.23 mm), Ø grooves = 45 in (11.43 mm), land width = .147 in (3.73 mm) and the primer type is large pistol.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The cartridge headspaces on the mouth of the case at the L3 datum reference.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] According to Commission internationale permanente pour l'épreuve des armes à feu portatives (CIP) rulings, the .45 ACP cartridge case can handle up to 131 MPa (19,000 psi) Pmax piezo pressure.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In CIP-regulated countries every pistol cartridge combination has to be proofed at 130% of this maximum CIP pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This means that .45 ACP chambered arms in CIP-regulated countries are currently (2016) proof-tested at 170 MPa (25,000 psi) PE piezo pressure.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .45 ACP is set at 21,000 psi (144.79 MPa) piezo pressure, while the SAAMI pressure limit for the .45 ACP +P is set at 23,000 psi (158.58 MPa), piezo pressure.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The .45 ACP is an effective combat pistol cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] It combines accuracy as well as stopping power for use against human targets, has relatively low muzzle blast and flash, and it produces moderate recoil in handguns (made worse in compact models or with hot loads).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The .45 ACP is generally considered to have greater stopping power than the 9mm.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Due to its larger size and slower velocity it creates a larger wound channel and transfers more energy to the target.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The standard-issue, military .45 ACP cartridge contains a 230-grain (15 g) bullet that travels at approximately 830 feet per second (253 m/s) when fired from the government-issue M1911A1 pistol, and approximately 950 feet per second (290 m/s) fired from the Thompson M1A1 submachine gun.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The cartridge comes in various specialty rounds of varying weights and performance levels as well.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Some makers of pistols chambered in .45 ACP do not certify them to use +P ammunition.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In its non-expanding full metal jacket (FMJ) version, the .45 ACP cartridge has a reputation for effectiveness against human targets because of its heavy mass, having the capacity to penetrate tissue deeply, and damage the central nervous system.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Its large 11.5 mm diameter creates a more substantial permanent wound channel versus smaller calibers, which can lower blood pressure rapidly if critical organs of the circulatory system are hit.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In its expanding hollow point form, it is also particularly effective against human targets.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In tests against ballistic gelatin, a 185-grain (12.0 g) hollow point traveling at 1,050 feet per second (320 m/s) expanded to about .76 inches (19 mm).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This is a significantly large permanent wound cavity for a handgun projectile.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] For those who follow the energy dump and/or hydrostatic shock theories of wounding ballistics, this is ideal.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] While slightly decreasing penetration and likewise the chance of hitting a vital organ, a large diameter wound will cause more blood loss.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] There is also a reduced likelihood of overpenetration, meaning that it is more likely that the projectile will transfer all of its kinetic energy to the intended target, thus more reliably incapacitating them.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Drawbacks for military use include the cartridge's large size, weight, and increased material costs in comparison to the smaller, flatter shooting NATO standard 9×19mm Parabellum cartridge, a cartridge which uses less powder, brass, and lead per round.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Standard 9mm NATO ammunition has a more limited armor penetration capability—a deficiency shared with .45 ACP, whose large, slow bullet does not penetrate armor to any great extent.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The low muzzle velocity also makes the bullet drop more over long ranges, making hits more difficult; the vast majority of self-defense situations involving handguns typically occur at close ranges.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] After two years of testing, one of the final FBI comments was that services that adopt (or stay with) .40 S&W or .45 ACP, did so at the risk of increased recoil and a possible reduction in accuracy as 9×19mm with premium quality ammunition had nearly exactly the same performance.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] A factor rated by the recent FBI testing was accuracy and time to recover.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The .45 ACP handguns ranked last, largely due to increased recoil.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] As standard pressure .45 ACP rounds fired from handguns and submachine guns are inherently subsonic, it is one of the most powerful pistol calibers available for use in suppressed weapons since subsonic rounds are quieter than supersonic rounds.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The latter inevitably produce a highly compressed shock wave, audible as a loud "crack", a small sonic boom, while they travel through the air.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Suppressors reduce the audible "report" by slowing and channeling the high speed gas generated by the burning/expanding gunpowder before it exits the muzzle resulting in a muffled "cough".
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The downside to the use of .45 ACP in suppressed weapons is that increasing the diameter of the passage through a suppressor decreases the suppressor's efficiency; thus, while .45 ACP is among the most powerful suppressed pistol rounds, it is also one of the loudest.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Most .45 ACP suppressors must be fired "wet" (with an ablative medium, usually oil or water) to bring sound levels down to "hearing-safe" (under 140 dB, generally).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Magazine capacity varies depending on the type of firearm.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Standard (not extended) single-stack magazines for pistols based on the 1911 design commonly hold eight rounds or fewer in .45 ACP.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Many modern pistols, such as the Glock 21, have adapted the cartridge into double-stacked magazine designs to increase ammo capacity, though this increases the pistol grip's girth.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Drum magazines used mostly for submachine guns have a capacity of 50 or 100 rounds.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Several US tactical police units still use the .45 pistol round.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The greater length and diameter of the .45 ACP means that the grip of the pistol must be longer and wider than the grip of a comparable pistol of a smaller caliber, such as 9×19mm Parabellum; this increase in grip size can make the pistol difficult to use for shooters with smaller hands.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Today, most NATO militaries use sidearms chambered for the 9×19mm Parabellum cartridge, but the effectiveness of the .45 ACP cartridge has ensured its continued popularity with large-caliber sport shooters, especially in the United States.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In addition, select military and police units around the world still use firearms firing the .45 ACP.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In 1985, the .45 ACP M1911A1 pistol was replaced by the Beretta M9 9mm pistol as the main sidearm of the U.S. military, although select Special Operations units continue to use the M1911A1 or other .45 ACP pistols.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Rounds are available from 68-to-300-grain (4.4 to 19.4 g) with a common load being the standard military loading of a 230-grain (15 g) FMJ bullet (for comparison, the most common 9mm load is 115 grains (7.5 g), half the weight).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Specialty rounds are available in weights under 100 grains (6.5 g) and over 260 grains (17 g); popular rounds among reloaders and target shooters include 185-to-230-grain (12.0 to 14.9 g) bullets.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Target shooters competing in Bullseye Pistol (aka Precision Pistol) find that .45 ACP ammunition using light bullets (12 to 13 g) and low velocities paradoxically generates less recoil than 9mm ammunition of equivalent accuracy, despite its larger caliber, and allows better scores in sustained fire.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Hollow-point rounds intended for maximum effectiveness against live targets are designed to expand upon impact with soft tissue, increasing the size of the permanent cavity left by the bullet as it passes through the target.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Tracer ammunition for the .45 ACP was manufactured by Frankford Arsenal and by Remington Arms.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This ammunition was available to the United States Border Patrol as early as 1940 and was used through World War II for emergency signalling by downed United States Navy and Marine Corps air crew.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Tracer ammunition was identified by painting the bullet tip red.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Most ammunition manufacturers also market what are termed "+P" (pronounced "plus P", designating overpressure ammunition) loadings in pistol ammunition, including the .45 ACP.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This means the cartridge is loaded to a higher maximum pressure level than the original SAAMI cartridge standard, generating higher velocity and more muzzle energy.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] In the case of the .45 ACP, the new standard cartridge pressure is 21,000 psi (145 MPa) and the SAAMI .45 ACP +P standard is 23,000 psi (159 MPa).
[src:air-gun/45-acp] This is a common practice for updating older cartridges to match the better quality of materials and workmanship in modern firearms.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The terminology is generally given as "45 ACP +P" and sometimes, but not always, appears on the headstamp.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] These cartridges have the same external dimensions as the standard-pressure cartridges and will chamber and fire in all firearms designed for the standard-pressure loadings.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The inner dimensions of the +P cartridge are different from the standard-pressure cartridge dimensions and thus allows for higher pressures to be safely achieved in the +P cartridge.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] If +P loadings are used in firearms not specifically designed for them, they may cause damage to the weapon and injuries to the operator.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Popular derivative versions of the .45 ACP are .45 Super and .460 Rowland.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The Super is dimensionally identical to the .45 ACP; however, the cartridge carries a developer established pressure of 28,500 psi (197 MPa) and requires minor modification of firearms for use.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The Rowland operates at a developer established 40,000 psi (276 MPa) SAAMI and may only be used within a select group of firearms significantly modified for this purpose; the Rowland case is 0.057 inches (1 mm) longer specifically to prevent it from being chambered in standard .45 ACP firearms.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] Brass cases for each of these cartridges carry the applicable name within the headstamp.
[src:air-gun/45-acp] The Super provides approximately 20% greater velocity than the .45 ACP +P; the Rowland approximately 40% greater velocity than the .45 ACP +P.
[src:air-gun/58-caliber] This is a list of firearm cartridges which have bullets that are 13 millimetres (0.51 in) to 13.99 millimetres (0.551 in) in caliber.
[src:air-gun/58-caliber] Note that dimensions do not always reflect the actual dimensions.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:air-gun/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:air-gun/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
